(1) Read Write Own: Building the Next Era of the Internet [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/235890c1-b8cb-476b-b926-24593fa06054?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
By Chris Dixon
Packy here. There=E2=80=99s a short list of people who have most influenced=
 my writing at Not Boring: Ben Thompson, Tim Urban, and Chris Dixon are at =
the top of the list.=20
Back in February last year, I got to read an advanced copy of Tim Urban=E2=
=80=99s book, What=E2=80=99s Our Problem?, and shared my thoughts [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/a1f96b89-fe9b-4dc4-aa34-d90862565980?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] on it in the Weekly D=
ose. With the benefit of hindsight, the arguments he made seem prescient an=
d correct.=20
Recently, Chris sent me an advance copy of his book, Read Write Own: Buildi=
ng the Next Era of the Internet [ https://substack.com/redirect/a1f96b89-fe=
9b-4dc4-aa34-d90862565980?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which goes on sale Tuesday. I ripped through it. With =
the benefit of hindsight, in a few years, the case he makes for blockchain =
networks will look prescient and correct.=20
Chris writes with a blend of history, technology, and philosophy, distilled=
 into well-reasoned and timeless takeaways.=20
His essays from over a decade ago =E2=80=94 The next big thing will start o=
ut looking like a toy [ https://substack.com/redirect/236ae643-34bc-42f0-bc=
39-2b98eb51ba98?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ], What the smartest people do on the weekend is what everyone else=
 will do during the week in ten years [ https://substack.com/redirect/1e203=
c50-c6ab-4db5-8382-6f31c4c47fd2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], The idea maze [ https://substack.com/redirect/10=
fce605-0a54-4f14-89a7-488626dac2df?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=94 show up linked in Not Boring posts t=
o this day. I referenced his 2018 post Why decentralization matters [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/50e71188-f5ec-4620-aa81-09ea0cd8533e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and the attract=E2=
=80=94>extract cycle he introduced in it in the first essay I ever wrote ab=
out crypto [ https://substack.com/redirect/19b0c26d-57c7-4153-bef0-d7813878=
90e1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=
=20
Over the past couple of years, I=E2=80=99ve gotten the chance to work with =
Chris and the a16z crypto team as an advisor. Their technology-focused pers=
pective on crypto has helped me to remain optimistic about its potential th=
rough the market=E2=80=99s ups and downs and influenced the way I think and=
 write about the space. I recently wrote Capitalism Onchained [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/b739f53a-8703-48fb-b78d-0b59dbd9b12c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and Blockchains as Platfo=
rms [ https://substack.com/redirect/6a1fc8bd-f9be-444d-9ce5-fc024da5f033?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] after s=
pending time with the team.=20
Read Write Own tells the history and future of the internet. It=E2=80=99s a=
 no hype, well-reasoned case that blockchain networks are both necessary fo=
r a richer internet and inevitable. It focuses on the technology and busine=
ss models =E2=80=94 the =E2=80=9Ccomputer=E2=80=9D as Chris calls it =E2=80=
=94 instead of the token prices and wild swings =E2=80=94 the =E2=80=9Ccasi=
no.=E2=80=9D As a result, I think this is a book that, like the essays, wil=
l be as relevant in a decade as it is today.=20
If the best way to predict the future is to see the present clearly, this b=
ook is the best prediction of the future of crypto, and of the internet, th=
at I=E2=80=99ve read.=20
As Chris writes, =E2=80=9CTales of fortunes won and lost are dramatic, easy=
 to explain, and attention grabbing. In contrast, the technology story is n=
uanced, slow to develop, and requires historical context to understand. (Th=
at=E2=80=99s a big reason why I wrote this book.)=E2=80=9D There=E2=80=99s =
no better person to write crypto=E2=80=99s story and divine its future.=20
Whether you already believe that crypto will be important or remain skeptic=
al, I think you=E2=80=99ll come away more optimistic after reading Read Wri=
te Own. Order it.
I want everyone to read the book. I=E2=80=99ll buy copies for the first 10 =
people who tweet about it with the link [ https://substack.com/redirect/235=
890c1-b8cb-476b-b926-24593fa06054?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] or a cover of the image and tag me @packym [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/a5b73819-fc4e-47d0-a7b9-ca1b03d01330?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
(2) Gene Therapy Allows an 11-Year-Old Boy to Hear for the First Time [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/81bef2ac-98fd-4d60-aba0-96cd0d5e8237?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Gina Kolata for the New York Times
On Oct. 4, Aissam was treated at the Children=E2=80=99s Hospital of Philade=
lphia, becoming the first person to get gene therapy in the United States f=
or congenital deafness. The goal was to provide him with hearing, but the r=
esearchers had no idea if the treatment would work or, if it did, how much =
he would hear.
The treatment was a success, introducing a child who had known nothing of s=
ound to a new world.
You heard that right: Children=E2=80=99s Hospital of Philadelphia (CHOP) do=
ctors used gene therapy to cure a case of congenital deafness. The therapy =
involved injecting a harmless virus carrying functional otoferlin genes int=
o the cochlea of the ear to replace the mutated gene, with the goal of rest=
oring hearing. And it worked! Prior to this, there was no biological or med=
ical methods to correct the underlying genetic causes of inner ear dysfunct=
ion.
Once more: doctors used gene therapy to cure deafness. Science rocks.=20
This type of gene therapy could be used to treat other genetic hearing loss=
es, but also has a wide array of potential applications across other geneti=
c disorders like cystic fibrosis, muscle dystrophy, hemophilia, and a numbe=
r of other common and rate genetic disorders.=20
Fun little aside here: when I was 2 years old, CHOP doctors saved my life. =
I had an atrial septal defect =E2=80=94 a hole in my heart =E2=80=94 that r=
equired pretty invasive and risky surgery. The procedure went flawlessly an=
d here I am today with a pretty decent heart as far as I can tell. So whene=
ver I have the opportunity to amplify CHOP doctors=E2=80=99 work, I am goin=
g to to it.=20
(3) Prophylactic and long-lasting efficacy of senolytic CAR T cells against=
 age-related metabolic dysfunction [ https://substack.com/redirect/0865855a=
-a174-44d7-92a7-9bfcdf694b77?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Amor et al in Nature
Unlike small molecules, CAR T cells only require that the target antigen is=
 differentially expressed on target cells compared to normal tissues; moreo=
ver, as =E2=80=98living drugs=E2=80=99, these therapeutics have the potenti=
al to persist and mediate their potent effects for years after single admin=
istration12 [ https://substack.com/redirect/421b81b4-f9e9-4678-8f7f-4050aa8=
faf5f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=
 We have shown that CAR T cells targeting the cell-surface protein uPAR, wh=
ich is upregulated on senescent cells, can efficiently deplete senescent ce=
lls in young animals and reverse liver fibrosis.
Someone make sure Bryan Johnson reads this research! The study developed a =
therapy using a type of engineered T cells called "CAR T cells=E2=80=9D tha=
t are designed to target and eliminate senescent cells. Senescent cells are=
 aged cells that have stopped dividing and can no longer perform their norm=
al functions, and they contribute to aging s by releasing harmful substance=
s that can damage nearby healthy cells. So if you eliminate the senescent c=
ells, you can slow the aging processes.=20
The research is still early =E2=80=94 the findings are currently limited to=
 animal models =E2=80=94 but is promising in terms of future applications i=
n age-related conditions and metabolic diseases. The mice that underwent th=
e treatment experienced improved exercise capacity and metabolic function a=
fter just one dose. And interestingly, young mice that received the treatme=
nt experienced a delay in the onset of age-related symptoms =E2=80=94 meani=
ng the treatment could be preventative in nature.
Longevity research is getting wild. What do we think the average lifespan o=
f a child born in 2024 will be? Over/under 100?
(4) Bridge RNAs direct modular and programmable recombination of target and=
 donor DNA [ https://substack.com/redirect/518d3781-5ddc-4d53-bc5f-80776102=
cf99?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
h/t Patrick Hsu of Arc Institute
We demonstrate that the target-binding and donor-binding loops can be indep=
endently reprogrammed to direct sequence-specific recombination between two=
 DNA molecules.
What a big week for gene editing, huh?
Researchers discovered a new class of structured non-coding RNAs. These RNA=
s, named "Bridge RNAs," bind specifically to their encoded recombinase and =
allow for precise programming. Bridge RNAs are structured non-coding RNAs t=
hat facilitate sequence-specific recombination of DNA by independently base=
-pairing with both target and donor DNA, directing modular and programmable=
 genetic rearrangements.=20
In more simple language, Bridge RNAs enable genetic modifications without t=
he need for DNA double-strand breaks, which are typically associated with t=
raditional genome editing techniques like CRISPR. This reduces the risk of =
unintended genetic damage and allows for greater precision in gene editing,=
 insertion, and deletion.=20
(5) Altman Seeks to Raise Billions for Network of AI Chip Factories [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/4701c7aa-be18-48da-8606-af910e7a1c36?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
By Edward Ludlow [ https://substack.com/redirect/bc7c3459-1126-4b1c-b403-76=
a2e8ede89b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ], Dina Bass [ https://substack.com/redirect/7d148f06-1871-4868-8372-5d2=
2bc81a749?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ], Gillian Tan [ https://substack.com/redirect/6e8578d0-999c-401e-b3fd-4e=
b83ae6ae96?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ], and Rachel Metz [ https://substack.com/redirect/8bbd1f13-4c01-4cc7-8c=
cb-f28819140161?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] for Bloomberg
OpenAI Chief Executive Officer Sam Altman, who has been working to raise bi=
llions [ https://substack.com/redirect/92b5825a-aa42-4793-a84c-e55d04253ada=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] of do=
llars from global investors for a chip venture, aims to use the funds to se=
t up a network of factories to manufacture semiconductors, according to sev=
eral people with knowledge of the plans.
IT=E2=80=99S TIME TO FAB. Bloomberg reported this week that OpenAI CEO Sam =
Altman was in talks with a number of global investors to raise significant =
capital to build a network semiconductor manufacturing facilities, that cou=
ld take on the likes of TSMC, Samsung, and Intel. Beyond the obvious size o=
f the prize =E2=80=94 TSMC and Intel are worth a combined ~$750B =E2=80=94 =
Altman is reportedly motivated by his concern is that AI chip demand will o=
utpace AI chip supply, which would hinder AI deployment and progress.
Details are still sparse, but I=E2=80=99ll share a few thoughts here:
US-Based: Presumably, Altman will not build this network of fabs in Taiwan =
or elsewhere within the sphere of China=E2=80=99s influence. Another scaled=
 semiconductor fab under complete U.S. control is a major win of American n=
ational security.
First Customer: Demand for Altman=E2=80=99s chips, should they be near pari=
ty with other options on the market, should not be an issue. First, OpenAI =
is or will be in the near future one of the largest AI chip customers in th=
e world. It helps when your founder is also the now-untouchable CEO of your=
 largest potential customer. Second, if Altman is right and AI continues to=
 grow at unprecedented rates of adoption, demand generally shouldn=E2=80=99=
t be an issue.
Altman=E2=80=99s Big Bets: We can now add chip manufacturing to Altman=E2=
=80=99s list of big bets. He=E2=80=99s behind the (arguably) leading startu=
ps in AI, crypto, fusion, and longevity. Sam makes big bets and chip manufa=
cturing is no exception.
As noted, still super early stages here and we=E2=80=99re excited to follow=
 this story as it develops. If it does happen, we can add it to the growing=
 list of Techno-Industrial [ https://substack.com/redirect/122632e7-39a3-45=
81-96d0-5b17dcd66da6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ] startups changing the world with bits and atoms.=20
Bonus: Prophetic Introduces Morpheus-1 [ https://substack.com/redirect/8f15=
de02-007a-415b-a94e-9b3f542e7234?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Packy here. All those chips Sama is building are going to do more than just=
 chat.=20
A startup called Prophetic [ https://substack.com/redirect/24e558db-798e-45=
81-86a5-4e1283b523b9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ] just released a model called Morpheus-1. As the company  twe=
eted: =E2=80=9CUnlike LLMs, Morpheus-1 is not prompted with words and sente=
nces but rather brain states. And instead of generating words, Morpheus-1 g=
enerates ultrasonic holograms for neurostimulation to bring one to a lucid =
state.=E2=80=9D=20
In other words, it reads your brain state and sends back ultrasonic signals=
 to induce lucid dreams. I=E2=80=99ve never lucid dreamed, but it sounds ma=
gical: you become aware that you=E2=80=99re dreaming, and can even control =
the characters, narrative, and environment in the dream. Virtual reality, o=
n steroids, inside your own mind.=20
I suspect that as we push the limits of computers=E2=80=99 brains, we=E2=80=
=99ll also want to more deeply explore our own. Morpheus-1 is a step toward=
s making that dream a reality.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. If you have some time this weekend, check=
 out Alto [ https://substack.com/redirect/ea8fc8a2-93ea-4d8a-a2cb-90d991c37=
27e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=
=20
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tuesday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan + Packy

